b'In honor of #VeteransDay, we\xe2\x80\x99re sharing the story of our friend and former United States Marine, Jake Wood. He co-founded Team Rubicon to give military vets a way to continue their service when they get back home. Read Jake\xe2\x80\x99s story and the stories of other veterans like Sue, Sergeant Mike, and Dozer in his new book Once a Warrior. Feeling inspired? Consider donating to @TeamRubicon today.'

b"At Team Rubicon, they say every greyshirt has a story. This is the story of Lissie Hagerman. Lissie \xe2\x80\x9cDozer\xe2\x80\x9d Hagerman hails from Austin, Texas and is a US Air Force veteran of several years. Earning the nickname of \xe2\x80\x9cDozer\xe2\x80\x9d comes from her small-on-the-surface stature but larger-than-life personality which encourages, motivates, and inspires her teammates whenever out on service operations with Team Rubicon. Putting others' needs in front of her own as she leads teams towards helping others is a frequent act of Hagerman's, and one that embodies the spirit of being \xe2\x80\x9cBuilt to Serve\xe2\x80\x9d. Visit @teamrubicon to learn more and to donate."

b'In honor of Veterans Day, and in support of Jake Wood\xe2\x80\x99s new book Once a Warrior, we\xe2\x80\x99re proud to be sharing the stories behind the brave men and women known as the Greyshirts. At Team Rubicon, they say every greyshirt has a story. This is the story of Mike \xe2\x80\x9cTop\xe2\x80\x9d Washington. Master Gunnery Sergeant Michael \xe2\x80\x9cTop\xe2\x80\x9d Washington embodies the spirit of #BuilttoServe\xe2\x80\x9d with his decades of service in the Marines and years leading in the Seattle Fire Department. Serving others in any way possible is a mindset seen consistently in Washington and is a virtue he passes throughout his family, as seen in his daughter volunteering alongside him on current Team Rubicon service operations, and through his son, Mike Washington, who served in the USMC overseas with co-founder of Team Rubicon, Jake Wood. Visit @teamrubicon to learn more and to donate.'

b'In honor of Veterans Day, and in support of Jake Wood\xe2\x80\x99s new book Once a Warrior, we\xe2\x80\x99re proud to be sharing the stories behind the brave men and women known as the Greyshirts. @teamrubicon they say every greyshirt has a story. This is the story of Sue Johnson. A Maui, HI resident and Army veteran, Sue Johnson decided early on to not allow anything to stop her from serving others and finishing whatever it is that she wanted to accomplish. Johnson served in the US Army for several years and later in life, in between battles with cancer, continued to serve by donating her time and energy into service opportunities with Team Rubicon. Although many would see obstacles that seem tall enough to serve as a legitimate excuse, Johnson, being \xe2\x80\x9cBuilt to Serve\xe2\x80\x9d, chooses to scale those obstacles regularly and does so in the spirit of helping others, no matter the cost.\nVisit @teamrubicon to learn more and to donate.'

b'I started sharing my farming journey on social media because my family and friends wanted to follow.

b'I grew up on a farm in Northern California, though I never even considered being a farmer until I was about 24.\xc2\xa0

After literal blood, sweat, and tears, I founded Beaver Vineyards and planted my first vineyard in April of 2018.\xc2\xa0

b'Meet Friend of Carhartt Jessica Davila, a senior student in the ACC Code Welding program. She says, "I've been adjusting to a full-time work schedule at TD Industries since ACC has moved all of their classes to an online format. This semester is my last before I graduate which makes it a little bittersweet since the ACC's welding shop is closed. \xe2\x80\x8b

The work I do is in a fabrication shop. We build pipe manifolds for kitchens, bathrooms, and huge air conditioners that regulate fluid flow or gas. We build off of blueprints that are needed for different job sites, so for example, right now we're working on welding 300 flanges to 8" pipe for a chill water line that will be for a job site downtown. Once it's built, we deliver it to the job sites and it gets installed. \xe2\x80\x8b

As far as leaving my house for work during these times it's definitely stressful. You know, sharing tools or using the same machines that my coworkers use is something I constantly think about, but we are required to wear masks now, and we use Lysol wipes to clean our job boxes along with the tools in them. We have a limited number of people who can work in the shop, so we all keep our distance. I think we're all pretty happy that we still have a job, and we're still getting our forty-hour workweek in, especially during these difficult times. \xe2\x80\x8b

My word of advice for other essential workers is to be mindful of what your hands and work gloves touch. Be mindful of your surroundings along with the people you're surrounding yourself with. Personal health is important and is something that shouldn't be taken lightly. As construction workers, there's a stigma that we have to be tough as nails and never miss a day of work. This makes taking time off difficult to do, but it's not worth putting other coworkers at risk. \xe2\x80\x8b

What keeps me motivated is truly loving what I do and seeing the finished product when it comes to welding and building these manifolds. I can see and feel myself improving every day with help from the people I work with. They're extremely smart and innovative, so every day I learn a new way to do something which helps with that motivation!" #FriendsofCarhartt'

b"When putting on my first pair of Carhartt overalls 3 years ago, I never imagined the impact that it would have on me as a person, and for the industry. An industry that some said I didn't look the part. I set out to make a statement about the lack of representation in a wine industry that I found accidentally through the passing of my Haitian immigrant father. This tragic moment in time was the catalyst to the life that I live today. So from tragedy to triumph, my overalls are not just clothes that I choose to wear, they are my suit of armor that allow me to change hearts and change minds.

Choosing to own my story, is what allows me to own my message of changing the world by changing the game. #Ownyourstory
